COMMON.NAME: Barred Antshrike
SCIENTIFIC.NAME: Thamnophilus doliatus
SUBSPECIES.COMMON.NAME: Barred Antshrike (Caatinga)
SUBSPECIES.SCIENTIFIC.NAME: Thamnophilus doliatus capistratus
TRIP.COMMENTS: Parte dos resultados publicados em Olmos, Girão & Albano (2005 ). Aves AVES EM OITO ÁREAS DE CAATINGA NO SUL DO CEARÁ E OESTE DE PERNAMBUCO, NORDESTE DO BRASIL: COMPOSIÇÃO, RIQUEZA E SIMILARIDADE. Papéis Avulsos de Zoologia 45(14). Área de caatinga arbóreo-arbustiva densa (copa a 6-8 m) dominada por marmeleiros e juremas, mostrando sinais de retirada de madeira. Há vários açudes de bom porte nas proximidades, com muitas macrófitas onde foram feitos censos diferenciados de--aves aquáticas. Uma linha de drenagem (“baixa”) mantém árvores de grande porte (angicos com altura > 20 m) e diâmetro, remanescentes de antiga mata galeria.

COMMON.NAME: Amazon Kingfisher
SCIENTIFIC.NAME: Chloroceryle amazona
TRIP.COMMENTS: Área amostrada por Olmos, Girão & Albano AVES EM OITO ÁREAS DE CAATINGA NO SUL DO CEARÁ E OESTE DE PERNAMBUCO, NORDESTE DO BRASIL: COMPOSIÇÃO, RIQUEZA E SIMILARIDADE Papéis Avulsos de Zoologia 45(14):179-199, 2005. Lagoas temporárias ou semipermanentes, algumas de água salobra, situadas próximas à zona urbana de Petrolina. São circundadas por caatinga arbustiva densa bastante alterada pela retirada de lenha e também pelo lançamento de resíduos. Muitas lagoas têm peixes, especialmente tilápias Oreochromis niloticus, que atraem aves piscívoras.

COMMON.NAME: American Kestrel
SCIENTIFIC.NAME: Falco sparverius
LOCALITY: Serra do Pará, Santa Cruz do Capibaribe, Pernambuc
TRIP.COMMENTS: Esta lista é resultado de dois anos de trabalho na Serra do Pará, realizado durante as coletas de campo do meu Doutorado. 19/junho/2011 até 26/maio/2013. Coletas mensais, totalizando 24 meses de observação. Falta complementar com o primeiro ano ainda e os registros feitos durante o mestrado. Esta Serra está localizada na região conhecida como Planalto da Borborema. Caracterizada por vegetação de caatinga-arbustivo-arbórea (predominam espécies de plantas das famílias das Cactaceae. Bromeliaceae e Euphorbiaceae), com afloramentos rochosos denominados de lajedos na região. Altitude 740 metros no seu ponto mais alto. Eu trabalhei no entorno, sopé e até o topo da Serra. No entorno, a região é conhecida como Vila do Pará, uma área mais rural, caracterizada por uma caatinga arbustiva e antropizada, com fazendas e sítios, criação de caprino e ovino, retirada de madeira. Tem várias fazendas com "vales" de algarobas, uma espécie exótica que foi introduzida no semiárido na década de 60.

COMMON.NAME: American Kestrel
SCIENTIFIC.NAME: Falco sparverius
LOCALITY: Fazenda Brejo, Parque Nacional Vale do Catimbau
TRIP.COMMENTS: Esses dados são referentes as minhas coletas de pós-doutorado e que também fazem parte de um projeto maior. O PARNA Catimbau é um sítio PELD (Programa Ecológico de Longa Duração). Estava acompanhada da Bruna Mirely. Estou apresentando apenas a lista qualitativa que contemplou as espécies registradas durantes os meus 10 pontos de escuta e no deslocamento da Vila Catimbau até a Fazenda Brejo. São 10 pontos de escuta distantes 200m. São 10 minutos por ponto e estou trabalhando com o raio de detecção de 50 metros e distância ilimatada. Eu ainda não tabulei os dados quantitativos. Esse período na região é de trovoada, que até eu sair de lá (dia 16/10) ainda não havia caído. O inverno mesmo (chuva) só a partir de Março, se ela vier (tem 3 anos que não chove direito. Conversei com as pessoas da região perguntando sobre a dinâmica das chuvas nos últimos tempos). Os últimos dias estavam bem nublados e caiu uma leve garoa, leve mesmo, como um borrifador no dia 14/10. Tem muitas ornitófilas floridas: Neoglaziovia variegata, Tacinga inamoena, Tacinga palmadora, Passiflora encarnata, Jatropha mutabilis, então estava bombando de beija-flores (abundância) e muitos jovens.

COMMON.NAME: Alagoas Tyrannulet
SCIENTIFIC.NAME: Phylloscartes ceciliae
TRIP.COMMENTS: Walked from visitor center along western portion of interpretive trail to its junction (7:30am) and onto the large rock by a jackfruit tree with interpretive signe (lft here at 8:28am), and then to Bernandina property (-08.71231, -35.85790) by 9:30am and lakes (Lagoa Matumbo -08.71269, -35.85605, Lagoa Amarelho  -08.71565, -35.85395). Not sure of precise time started for next checklist, but 10:30am makes a good rough guess. Most vocalizations identified by Pedro.
SPECIES.COMMENTS: At interpretive trail junction in mixed flock with with Blue Dacnis, Little Woodpecker, Var.Antshrike, Plain Xenops, Guira Tanager, Elaenia sp., Red-eyed Vireo (Chivi), Violaceous Euphonia. Small tyrannulet with horizontal posture, clear wingbars, diffuse face pattern (eye-line and paler superciliary), pale belly perched high in canopy of tree up hill to west. Better views desired.

COMMON.NAME: Alagoas Tyrannulet
SCIENTIFIC.NAME: Phylloscartes ceciliae
TRIP.COMMENTS: Birding the dirt roads around the dam. Mostly looking for the Pygmy-tyrant (dipped) and the kite. Rain showers off and on all day with continuous rain starting at 1400. When we drove up the road it was dry and very doable in a small rental. By the time we left, the roads were very slippery and the descent was very dangerous. No clue how we didn't get seriously stuck. We literally slide down with no traction. If you're at the top and it starts raining, you need to leave immediately. Entrance road starts at -8.747906 -35.815855. Take a left at -8.745575, -35.815343 and another left at -8.73478, -35.817048. Keep right at -8.732534 -35.822306, keep left -8.730328, -35.830344, keep right at -8.735674, -35.838073, and keep right at -8.7276, -35.83871. At the final fork (-8.72022 -35.837107) left will take you up to the dam, but right will take you uphill to the soccer field at -8.718257, -35.836162. Once you reach the dam, the ranger's house is to the right. There are trails behind the property or you can continue left around the damn to some other areas.

COMMON.NAME: Alagoas Tyrannulet
SCIENTIFIC.NAME: Phylloscartes ceciliae
TRIP.COMMENTS: Contact Barbara at serradourubu@savebrasil.org.br to make a reservation to visit. They are open Monday-Saturday and hours are 0700-1600, but that is very flexible. We showed up to the gate at dawn and birded the open area near the gate. At 0700 we let ourselves in as the gate was unlocked and the family at the building was expecting us. I'm sure if you went in at 0530 or 0600 they wouldn't mind. They also didn't care what time we left so we stayed until 1700. The first time along the trail the guy showed us good spots for Orange-bellied Antwren and usually where people find Alagoas Tyrannulet. After that we spent the rest of the day on our own. There's only one main trail through the forest. Directions: Start of road is at -8.652608, -35.90028. Take a right at -8.654253 -35.895392, and then keep right at -8.65845 -35.88597, keep left at -8.662602, -35.87867, take a right at -8.674394 -35.860988, and then a left at -8.683217, -35.865278. The entrance gate is at -8.692957, -35.856602. The road is dirt and steep in places. Probably not passable in a normal vehicle if its been raining (too slippery).
SPECIES.COMMENTS: Near the same area as the antwrens

COMMON.NAME: Bananaquit
SCIENTIFIC.NAME: Coereba flaveola
TRIP.COMMENTS: Afternoon at visitor center station, from about 1:45pm on. We might have seen 1 female Racket-tailed Coquette Discosura longicaudus perched, with slightly crested head, green back, whitish rump band; possibly saw white malar. Originally idientified in field as Racket-tailed Coquette, but all subsequent observations of coquette were of a female Frilled Coquete which later gave me doubt about this initial observation.

COMMON.NAME: Brown Noddy
SCIENTIFIC.NAME: Anous stolidus
TRIP.COMMENTS: Brown Noddy sighting represents second personal notable pelagic bird sighting from this beach in five years of intermittant observing. First was Greater Shearwater December 25, 2019.
SPECIES.COMMENTS: While at beach, observed a brown noddy land briefly at close range, then fly south following coast until out of sight. Many field marks observed including larger size, dark brown overall plumage; long, dark bll, and in flight: a leisurely pattern of strong, steady wingbeats, with a height only a couple of meters above the ocean. It followed the coast directly into a 10-knot SE wind. Lack of well-developed white cap indicates perhaps a juvenile. Stray possibly from Fernando do Noronho archipelago, as there have been two days of stormy, unsettled weather.

COMMON.NAME: Blue-backed Manakin
SCIENTIFIC.NAME: Chiroxiphia pareola
TRIP.COMMENTS: with Stephen Jones. This report has been called into question by eBird concerning the report of five Ash-throated Crakes. It shouldn't have called into question for the following reasons. 1. There were at least five ash-throated crakes present, that is for sure. Two were seen. 2. This is not a hard bird to identify both by sound and sight. 3. Ash-throated crakes, while not often reported, are fairly well represented in proper habitat in Pernambuco. 4. The wet area from which these birds were reported from, although large in itself, is only a small portion of the total wet area in the vicinity. Again, undoubtably many more are present. 5. They responded to playback. 6. They were witnessed by two observers who tally at least 70-years of collective birdwatching between them. Furthermore, the two observors currently are numbers 1 and 2 respectively for the Permanbuco eBird species total. Finally, with respects to the moderator who called this report into question, he apparantly is from a Brazilian state over a thousand miles away. While he perhaps has some birdwatching experience in Pernambuco, I would invite him, or anyone,  to where we were and hear and see the Ash-throated crakes for themselves.

COMMON.NAME: Brown Noddy
SCIENTIFIC.NAME: Anous stolidus
TRIP.COMMENTS: Remarkably, the second sighting of a Brown Noddy from this location on the coast within a month.
SPECIES.COMMENTS: Noddy landed within meters of my location at the beach. I was able to take a number of photos with a point and shoot camera. From its original perch on a decrepit seawall, it flew to the water and swam within meters of the seawall for a few minutes. Then it flew into a housing area and landed on a lawn and I was unable to persue it further. Clearly it was either extremely exhausted or in serious trouble. Most likely the waif was from the offshore islands of Fernando do Noronha. Juvenile or immature.
